  "text": "We consider the problem that an external agent, the briber, who knows the CP-nets of all voters, asks them to execute changes in their cp-statements. Mattei et al. [CITATION_1] define this in a way that the briber can ask the voters to flip the value of one or more issues in their CP-nets, which might imply several further changes, according to the dependencies. They distinguish the case that the briber can ask for a change in the cp-statements of the independent issues only (IV), the dependent issues only (DV), or in any cp-statement (IV+DV). Moreover, they introduce five cost schemes:",
